T1  - Augmenting Markets with Mechanisms
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdaa064
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 88
IS  - 4
SP  - 1665
EP  - 1719
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We explain how the common practice of size-discovery trade detracts from overall financial market efficiency. At each of a series of size-discovery sessions, traders report their desired trades, generating allocations of the asset and cash that rely on the most recent exchange price. Traders can thus mitigate exchange price impacts by waiting for size-discovery sessions. This waiting causes socially costly delays in the rebalancing of asset positions across traders. As the frequency of size-discovery sessions is increased, exchange market depth is further lowered by the traders’ reduced incentive to bid aggressively on the exchange, further delaying the rebalancing of positions, and more than offsetting the gains from trade that occur at each of the size-discovery sessions.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdaa064
ER  - 



